          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the muscle biopsy of a patient with Duchenne muscular dystrophy, which histol</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the muscle biopsy of a patient with Duchenne muscular dystrophy, which histological feature distinguishes regenerating fibres from healthy ones?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Peripherally placed nuclei</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Peripheral nuclei are the normal finding in healthy skeletal muscle fibres. Regenerating fibres characteristically shift their nuclei to a central position.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Presence of intercalated discs</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Intercalated discs are the diagnostic feature of cardiac muscle, not skeletal muscle. Regenerating skeletal muscle fibres are identified by their centrally placed nuclei.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Centrally placed nuclei</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! In healthy skeletal muscle, multiple nuclei are pushed to the periphery beneath the sarcolemma. During regeneration, nuclei shift to a central position — a reliable histological marker of active fibre repair.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Loss of cross-striations</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Loss of striations indicates severe myofibrillar disruption rather than regeneration. The hallmark of regenerating skeletal muscle fibres is centrally placed nuclei.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the biopsy findings described in the case. Healthy fibres have peripheral nuclei; regenerating fibres shift them centrally — this distinction is a high-yield identification point."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Central nuclei are a key histological marker of skeletal muscle regeneration, commonly tested in MBBS examinations."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
