          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>What is the primary functional role of gap junctions in the intercalated discs o</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What is the primary functional role of gap junctions in the intercalated discs of cardiac muscle?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Mechanically anchoring adjacent cardiac cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Mechanical coupling is the role of fascia adherens in the transverse portion of the intercalated disc. Gap junctions allow ion flow between cells for coordinated contraction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Allowing rapid spread of electrical impulses, creating a functional syncytium</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Gap junctions in the lateral portions of the intercalated disc permit direct ion passage between cardiac cells, spreading the action potential almost instantaneously and enabling the heart to contract as a single coordinated unit.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Storing calcium ions for excitation-contraction coupling</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Calcium storage is the function of the sarcoplasmic reticulum, not gap junctions. Gap junctions in the intercalated disc serve an electrical coupling function between cardiac cells.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Providing attachment sites for actin filaments</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Actin filament anchorage occurs at fascia adherens and Z-discs. Gap junctions serve an entirely different purpose — enabling the heart to beat as a functional syncytium through electrical coupling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember that the intercalated disc has two distinct functional zones: the transverse portion (fascia adherens for mechanical coupling) and the lateral portions (gap junctions for electrical coupling as a functional syncytium)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent! Understanding the structure-function relationship of the intercalated disc is essential — fascia adherens provides mechanical coupling, while gap junctions provide electrical coupling."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
