          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In skeletal muscle, the triad at the A-I band junction consists of which combina</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In skeletal muscle, the triad at the A-I band junction consists of which combination of structures?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>One T-tubule flanked by two terminal cisternae of the sarcoplasmic reticulum</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The skeletal muscle triad is located at the A-I band junction and comprises one transverse tubule flanked by two terminal cisternae. This arrangement ensures rapid and simultaneous calcium release for excitation-contraction coupling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Two T-tubules flanking one terminal cisterna of the sarcoplasmic reticulum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This reverses the actual arrangement. The triad has one central T-tubule flanked by two terminal cisternae on either side, not the other way around.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>One T-tubule paired with one cisterna at the Z-line</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>One T-tubule paired with one cisterna at the Z-line describes the dyad found in cardiac muscle, not the triad of skeletal muscle. The triad has two cisternae and is located at the A-I junction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Three T-tubules surrounding a single myofibril</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The name 'triad' refers to three structural elements — one T-tubule plus two terminal cisternae — not three T-tubules. Each triad serves one sarcomere's excitation-contraction coupling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Recall from the ultrastructure section: skeletal muscle has a triad (1 T-tubule + 2 terminal cisternae at the A-I junction), while cardiac muscle has a dyad (1 T-tubule + 1 cisterna at the Z-line)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The triad (skeletal) versus dyad (cardiac) distinction is a frequently examined ultrastructural concept."
                }
              ],
